:"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde de Mirebeau was born about 1209. She married Guillaume de Brenne about 1231. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"UM 1209–":"umbes 1209–Surnud","1201–1256":"1201–1256","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1209–Female":"1209–Surnud","UM 1209":"umbes 1209","1235":"1235","1256":"1256","1201":"1201","UM 1231":"umbes 1231","1209":"1209","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"UM 1209–":"noin 1209–Kuollut","1201–1256":"1201–1256","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1209–Female":"1209–Kuollut","UM 1209":"noin 1209","1235":"1235","1256":"1256","1201":"1201","UM 1231":"noin 1231","1209":"1209","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"UM 1209–":"environ 1209